pr_review_body:
@sophiazhi Thanks a lot for your work. LGTM.

I am approving this PR on the basis that the model achieves decent accuracy for its size and that unblocks Multimodal. On the cons side, we are using ported weights from an unofficial repo which seem to be lagging by 5 accuracy points comparing to the paper. To mitigate this I have:
1. [Pinged](https://github.com/pytorch/vision/pull/6412#issuecomment-1219687434) the author of the repo to clarify the exact inference setup they use.
2. Started an internal job (id 55651) to train the network from scratch and potentially replace the weights if we get better accuracy.

Since the gap in accuracy is on the borderline of what we usually consider acceptable and because I've made multiple commits on the PR, I would like a second opinion on how we should progress here.

@jdsgomes @langong347 Please let me know your thoughts.

I have 2 strong requirement; 

1. Can you add a cpp unit test to calculate the # of pending tasks? Make sure it is correctly incremented and decremented when tasks are replied / submitted
2. Can you improve the error message? This is user-facing error, and making it clear is very important for this kind of feature.

Nice @JRMeyer, just missing the following on the IDeepSpeech interface:

```
        /// <summary>
        /// Add a hot-word.
        /// </summary>
        /// <param name="aWord">Some word</param>
        /// <param name="aBoost">Some boost</param>
        /// <exception cref="ArgumentException">Thrown on failure.</exception>
        public void AddHotWord(string aWord, float aBoost);

        /// <summary>
        /// Erase entry for a hot-word.
        /// </summary>
        /// <param name="aWord">Some word</param>
        /// <exception cref="ArgumentException">Thrown on failure.</exception>
        public void EraseHotWord(string aWord);

        /// <summary>
        /// Clear all hot-words.
        /// </summary>
        /// <exception cref="ArgumentException">Thrown on failure.</exception>
        public void ClearHotWords();
```

@brianljt thank you for this.

Shouldn't we reference to power on the antenna connector for each functionality, and so add/decrement the offset (LNA Gain) in the following functions:

`nrf_802154_energy_detected`, `nrf_802154_received_timestamp_raw`, `nrf_802154_transmitted_raw`, `otPlatRadioGetRssi`?

For example:
```
void nrf_802154_energy_detected(uint8_t result)
{
    sEnergyDetected = nrf_802154_dbm_from_energy_level_calculate(result) - sLnaGain;

    setPendingEvent(kPendingEventEnergyDetected);
}
```

Looks good, thank you!

Does it make sense maybe to also block the `disconnect` handler, even if it might be overridden by a contrib?

```
def _disconnect(remote, *args, **kwargs):
    """Common logic for handling disconnection of remote accounts."""
    if not current_user.is_authenticated:
        return current_app.login_manager.unauthorized()
    
    if only_one_account:
        abort(...)
```

I propose to converge with #324 to co-author something to:
- avoid duplicated reviews and stuffs;
- design something standardized.

I think you have 2 bugs that cancelled out in test cases here. I think some test like 

```
@ray.remote
def f():
 sleep(10000)

@ray.remote
def g():
 ray.get(h.remote())

@ray.remote
def h():
 sleep(10000)

ray.get([f.remote() for _ in range(10000)].extend([g.remote() for _ in range(1000)]))
```

will fail (note that the nested task is just one way of causing 2 tasks to have the same resource shape but separate scheduling classes. (it may not hurt to also have a test case with 2 tasks of the same resource shape but different scheduling classes, but i leave that up to you).

Thanks @andrei-menzopol. 
I think it will help to define the data structures and their format more clearly. We can specify the different types and constants:

```c++
/**
 * Max buffer size (in bytes) for representing the EDCSA key-pair in DER format.
 *
 */
#define OT_CRYPTO_ECDSA_MAX_DER_SIZE 125

/**
 * This structure represents an ECDSA key pair (public and private keys).
 *
 * The key pair is stored using Distinguished Encoding Rules (DER) format (per RFC 5915).
 *
 */
typedef struct otPlatCryptoEcdsaKeyPair
{
    uint8_t mDerBytes[OT_CRYPTO_ECDSA_MAX_DER_SIZE];
    uint8_t mDerLength;
} otPlatCryptoEcdsaKeyPair;


#define OT_CRYPTO_ECDSA_PUBLIC_KEY_SIZE 64 // Should check if it is correct

/**
 * This struct represents a ECDSA public key.
 *
 * The public key is stored as a byte sequence representation of an uncompressed curve point (RFC 6605 - sec 4).
 *
 */
OT_TOOL_PACKED_BEGIN
struct otPlatCryptoEcdsaPublicKey
{
    uint8_t m8[OT_CRYPTO_ECDSA_PUBLIC_KEY_SIZE];
}
OT_TOOL_PACKED_END;

typedef struct otPlatCryptoEcdsaPublicKey otPlatCryptoEcdsaPublicKey;

/**
 * This struct represents an ECDSA signature.
 *
 * The signature is encoded as the concatenated binary representation of two MPIs `r` and `s` which are calculated
 * during signing (RFC 6605 - section 4).
 *
 */
OT_TOOL_PACKED_BEGIN
struct otPlatCryptoEcdsaSignature
{
    uint8_t m8[...] (TODO)
};
```

And then we can define the platform APIs to mirror public methods of different `Ecdsa` classes:

```c++
otError otPlatCryptoEcdsaGenerateKey(otPlatCryptoEcdsaKeyPair *aKeyPair);

otError otPlatCryptoEcdsaGePublicKey(const otPlatCryptoEcdsaKeyPair *aKeyPair, otPlatCryptoEcdsaPublicKey *aPublicKey);

otError otPlatCryptoEcdsaSign(const otPlatCryptoEcdsaKeyPair *aKeyPair, 
                              const otCryptoSha256Hash *      aHash, 
                              otPlatCryptoEcdsaSignature *    aSignature);

otError otPlatCryptoEcdsaVerify(const otPlatCryptoEcdsaPublicKey *aPublicKey,
                                const otCryptoSha256Hash *      aHash,
                                const otPlatCryptoEcdsaSignature *    aSignature);
```
